# %%
import yfinance as yf
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from tabulate import tabulate
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import scipy.stats as stats
from scipy.stats import shapiro
import os

# Define tickers and friendly names
tickers = {
    "^NSEI": "Nifty",
    "^DJI": "DowJones",
    "^IXIC": "Nasdaq",
    "^HSI": "HangSeng",
    "^N225": "Nikkei",
    "^GDAXI": "DAX",
    "^VIX": "VIX",
}

start_date = "2018-11-01"
end_date = "2025-02-28"

# Download and keep only Open and Close
data_frames = {}
for ticker, name in tickers.items():
    data = yf.download(ticker, start=start_date, end=end_date)[['Open', 'Close']]
    data.columns = [f"{name}_Open", f"{name}_Close"]
    data_frames[name] = data

# Get full date range including all days (weekends and holidays included)
full_range = pd.date_range(start=start_date, end=end_date, freq='D')

# Remove weekends before interpolation
full_range = full_range[full_range.dayofweek < 5]

# Remove 1st of January of each year as this is a holiday in many markets
full_range = full_range[~((full_range.month == 1) & (full_range.day == 1))]


# Reindex each DataFrame and interpolate OPen and Close using both Open and Close info
for name, df in data_frames.items():
    df.index = pd.to_datetime(df.index)
    df = df.sort_index()
    df = df.reindex(full_range)

    open_col = f"{name}_Open"
    close_col = f"{name}_Close"

    # Interpolate Open and Close individually
    interpolated_open = df[open_col].interpolate(method='linear', limit_direction='both')
    interpolated_close = df[close_col].interpolate(method='linear', limit_direction='both')

    # Fill NaNs only, preserving original non-NaN values
    df[open_col] = df[open_col].combine_first(interpolated_open)
    df[close_col] = df[close_col].combine_first(interpolated_close)

    data_frames[name] = df

# Merge all into one master table
master_table = pd.concat(data_frames.values(), axis=1)


# Calculate daily returns (exclude VIX)
returns = pd.DataFrame(index=master_table.index)
for name in tickers.values():
    close_col = f"{name}_Close"
    if close_col in master_table.columns:
        return_col = f"{name}_Return"
        returns[return_col] = master_table[close_col].pct_change() * 100

# Merge returns into master_table
master_table = pd.concat([master_table, returns], axis=1)

# Add Year, Quarter, Month as new columns
master_table['Year'] = master_table.index.year
master_table['Quarter'] = master_table.index.quarter
master_table['Month'] = master_table.index.month


master_table = master_table[(master_table['Year'] >= 2019) & (master_table['Year'] <= 2024)]

shapiro_results = []

for col in master_table.columns:
    if col.endswith("_Return") and not col.startswith("VIX"):
        data = master_table[col].dropna()

        if len(data) < 30:
            continue

        # Q-Q Plot
        plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
        stats.probplot(data, dist="norm", plot=plt)
        plt.title(f'Q-Q Plot: {col}')
        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.close()

        # Shapiro-Wilk Test
        stat, p = shapiro(data)
        shapiro_results.append({
            'Index': col.replace("_Return", ""),
            'Shapiro_Stat': stat,
            'p_value': p,
            'Normality': 'Normal' if p > 0.05 else 'Not Normal'
        })


# Define index names
index_names = ["Nifty", "DowJones", "Nasdaq", "HangSeng", "Nikkei", "DAX"]

# Create 2 rows x 3 columns subplot grid
fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=3, figsize=(18, 10))

# Flatten axes array for easy access
axes = axes.flatten()

# Loop through indices and create Q-Q plots
for i, name in enumerate(index_names):
    data = master_table[f"{name}_Return"].dropna()
    stats.probplot(data, dist="norm", plot=axes[i])
    axes[i].set_title(f"Q-Q Plot: {name}", fontsize=12)

# Improve layout
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()


# Print test rsults
shapiro_df = pd.DataFrame(shapiro_results)
print(tabulate(shapiro_df, headers='keys', tablefmt='pretty'))

Normality Plots & Shapiro-Wilk Test Summary

This section assesses whether the daily return distributions for the major indices approximate a Normal (Gaussian) shape. Two complementary checks were used: Q-Q (normality) plots and the Shapiro-Wilk normality test.

Normality (Q-Q) Plot Interpretation

The Q-Q plots compare the empirical return quantiles against theoretical Normal quantiles. Across indices, the plotted points deviate from a straight lineespecially in the tailsindicating that returns exhibit fat tails (more extreme moves than a Normal distribution would predict) and mild skew / tail-asymmetry. In practical terms: the market delivers ordinary days most of the time, but it also produces too many unusually large up/down days for a Normal model to be a clean fit.

Shapiro-Wilk Test Results

The Shapiro-Wilk test formally evaluates Normality using the null hypothesis: the data are Normally distributed. For every index tested, the p-values are far below 0.05, meaning we reject Normality for all return series (Nifty, Dow Jones, Nasdaq, Hang Seng, Nikkei, and DAX).

Key Implication for Modelling

  • Assumption check: Standard Normal-based methods (e.g., classic parametric inference that leans heavily on Normality) should be used cautiously.
  • Practical takeaway: Volatility and tail-risk mattermethods robust to non-Normality (or models that explicitly handle heavy tails) are typically more realistic for financial return behaviour.

Summary

Both the visual diagnostics (Q-Q plots) and the Shapiro-Wilk tests consistently indicate that daily returns are not Normally distributed across all indices examined. This aligns with the well-known empirical reality of financial markets: returns tend to have heavier tails and occasional extreme movements that a Normal model understates.

Box-Whisker Plot Interpretation

The box-whisker plots illustrate the distribution of daily percentage returns for six major global indices Nifty 50, Dow Jones, Nasdaq, Hang Seng, Nikkei 225, and DAX across the period 2019 to 2024.

Overall Trends

Across all markets, median daily returns hover near zero, showing mean-reverting behaviour. The relatively narrow interquartile ranges indicate modest daily movement, while extended whiskers and outliers represent short bursts of volatility tied to market events.

COVID-19 Shock (2020)

Each index shows a noticeably wider spread and more extreme outliers in 2020, marking the extraordinary volatility that accompanied the onset of the pandemic. Dow Jones and Nasdaq display the sharpest downside extremes, while Nifty 50 and Hang Seng also experienced deep negative swings. Overall, 2020 was the most volatile year for global equities.

Post-COVID Normalization (2021 2023)

From 2021 onward, the interquartile ranges narrow, indicating a steady return to stability. Median returns remain near zero but turn slightly positive for Nasdaq and Nikkei, hinting at recovery in technology and export-driven sectors. Nifty 50 and DAX maintain modest, positive medians during this phase.

Recent Year (2024)

The 2024 distributions are tighter and less skewed, signalling lower volatility. Nifty 50 and Nasdaq continue to show mild positive central tendencies, while Hang Seng retains broader dispersion, reflecting ongoing uncertainty in Asian markets. Overall, the global indices converge toward market stability.

Comparative Insights

  • Highest Volatility: Dow Jones and Nasdaq (2020)
  • Most Stable Markets: Nikkei 225 and DAX (post-2021)
  • Consistent Performer: Nifty 50 balanced returns and fewer extremes after 2021
  • Persistent Dispersion: Hang Seng continued volatility beyond pandemic years

Summary

The plots reveal a clear volatility cycle: a sharp expansion during the 2020 global shock followed by contraction as markets stabilised. These findings set the foundation for correlation and predictive modelling in later phases, highlighting how systemic events create synchronized global volatility with differing regional recovery speeds.

Summary of Daily Returns by Year

The tables below quantify the average daily return (mean) and volatility (standard deviation) of each major global index from 2019 to 2024. Together with the box-whisker plots, these statistics highlight periods of extreme movement, recovery, and stabilization across international markets.

1. Nifty 50 (India)

Average daily returns remain positive throughout the period, peaking in 2021 (0.09%). Volatility surges in 2020 (sd = 1.87) during the pandemic shock, then normalizes below 1% thereafter. Nifty exhibits a consistent and resilient performance profile with modest year-on-year variability.

2. Dow Jones Industrial Average (U.S.)

Mean daily returns fluctuate narrowly around zero, but volatility spikes dramatically in 2020 (sd = 2.27). The index turns slightly negative in 2022 (mean = -0.03%) amid tightening monetary policy, before recovering to moderate stability in 2023-2024.

3. Nasdaq Composite (U.S.)

Nasdaq shows the highest overall mean returns among all indices, led by tech-sector momentum. Volatility peaks in 2020 (sd = 2.19) and again in 2022 (sd = 1.97) during the interest-rate correction. Strong rebound years (20232024) reflect sustained growth in innovation-driven equities.

4. Hang Seng Index (Hong Kong)

Distinctly different from Western markets, Hang Seng records negative mean returns from 2020 to 2023, coinciding with Chinas economic slowdown and property-sector stress. Volatility remains elevated across all years, especially 2022 (sd = 1.97). Only in 2024 (mean = 0.07%) does the index turn positive, hinting at tentative recovery.

5. Nikkei 225 (Japan)

Nikkeis performance is generally steady, with small positive returns most years. Volatility rises in 2020 (sd = 1.55) and again in 2024 (sd = 1.57), reflecting currency fluctuations and export uncertainty. The 2023 mean (0.10%) marks a particularly strong year for Japans equity market.

6. DAX (Germany)

DAX mirrors European macro-trends: stable gains in 2019 and 20212024 but a contraction in 2022 (mean = -0.04%) during energy-price shocks. The volatility pattern (sd = 2.03 in 2020) underscores the COVID-era turbulence. Subsequent years exhibit subdued variance (<1%), reflecting Europes economic normalization.

Comparative Insights

  • Highest Average Return: Nasdaq (2020 0.16%)
  • Highest Volatility: Dow Jones (2020 2.27 sd)
  • Most Stable Markets: Nifty 50 and DAX after 2021
  • Consistent Positive Performer: Nifty 50 steady gains with controlled volatility
  • Lagging Market: Hang Seng negative mean returns 20202023

Summary

Across all indices, the data confirm a pronounced volatility surge in 2020, followed by gradual normalization and selective outperformance in technology-oriented and emerging-market indices. The mean and standard-deviation patterns quantitatively support the visual findings from the box-whisker plots, emphasizing the global shock-and-recovery cycle that defines the 20192024 window.

close_columns = [
    "Nifty_Close",
    "DowJones_Close",
    "Nasdaq_Close",
    "HangSeng_Close",
    "Nikkei_Close",
    "DAX_Close"
]

# Plot each index with rolling and regression trend lines
for col in close_columns:
    index_name = col.replace("_Close", "")

    # Drop NA values for clean regression
    df = master_table[[col]].dropna()

    # Prepare regression variables
    x = df.index.map(pd.Timestamp.toordinal).values
    y = df[col].values

    # Linear regression fit
    slope, intercept = np.polyfit(x, y, 1)
    trend = slope * x + intercept

    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))

    # Daily Close
    sns.lineplot(data=master_table, x=master_table.index, y=col, label="Daily Close", color="#508C9B")

    # Linear regression trend (blue line)
    plt.plot(df.index, trend, label="Linear Trend", color="#911E7E", linewidth=1, dashes=(5, 5))

    # Plot formatting

Inter-Market Behaviour Analysis Global Index Reaction to Nifty Positive Open

This section investigates how frequently major global indices and the volatility index (VIX) record a positive daily return on days when the Nifty opens higher than the previous close. The analysis combines both tabular results and a visual summary to highlight which markets most often follow the Niftys positive open.

1. Analytical Approach

The analysis filters all trading days where Nifty opened positive (Nifty_Open_Dir = 1) and calculates, for each other index, the percentage of times its own daily return was also positive. The resulting follow-through percentage quantifies inter-market alignment or contagion in short-term sentiment.

2. Results Overview

The table of calculated values shows that on days when the Nifty opens positive:

  • Nikkei 225 follows suit about 65.6% of the time the highest co-movement rate.
  • DAX (59.7%), Hang Seng (58.9%), and Nasdaq (58.4%) also display solid alignment with the Niftys direction.
  • Dow Jones follows 57.4% of the time, indicating a moderate linkage.
  • VIX shows only 43.2% positive days, confirming its usual inverse relationship with equities.

3. Visual Insights

The horizontal bar chart visually reinforces these findings:

  • All major equity indices exhibit bars extending well above 50%, emphasizing the positive global sentiment spillover when the Nifty opens strong.
  • Nikkei 225 stands out with the darkest shade (Follows > 50%), representing the highest consistency of positive co-movement.
  • VIX is colored lighter ( 50%) to illustrate its opposite response volatility typically falls when markets rally.
  • The dotted vertical line at 50% serves as a neutral benchmark; indices to the right indicate more frequent joint positivity than randomness.

4. Interpretation

These results imply that Asian and European markets (especially Japan and Germany) show stronger synchronous movement with the Niftys intraday sentiment than the U.S. markets. The relatively lower association with the Dow and Nasdaq reflects the time-zone gap U.S. markets open after Indias close, reducing same-day response effects.

The consistently negative linkage of the VIX reaffirms its role as a fear index, rising when equities weaken and softening when optimism prevails.

5. Summary

When the Nifty opens on a positive note, most global markets tend to follow the upward momentum on the same day, with Japans Nikkei showing the highest rate of alignment. The analysis underscores a moderate but meaningful short-term correlation of global optimism, while volatility (VIX) predictably moves in the opposite direction. These inter-market reactions strengthen the case for incorporating global index movements as leading indicators in Nifty directional prediction models developed in subsequent phases.

# Step 2  create lagged features (t-1) and split 80/20

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

# Work on a copy
df = master_table.copy()

ret_cols = [
    "DowJones_Return", "Nasdaq_Return", "HangSeng_Return",
    "Nikkei_Return", "DAX_Return", "VIX_Return"
]

# Create lag-1 features so each row t uses information from t-1
lag_features = [f"{c}_lag1" for c in ret_cols]
for c in ret_cols:
    df[f"{c}_lag1"] = df[c].shift(1)

# Drop rows introduced by lag
df = df.dropna(subset=lag_features).copy()

target = "Nifty_Open_Dir"

y = df[target].astype(int)

    X, y, test_size=0.20, random_state=42, stratify=y
)

In[71]:
# Step 4  Multicollinearity (VIF). Iteratively drop features with VIF > 10.

try:
    import statsmodels.api as sm
    from statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence import variance_inflation_factor as vif

    def compute_vif(df_feats: pd.DataFrame) -> pd.DataFrame:
        X_ = sm.add_constant(df_feats, has_constant="add")
        vals = []
        for i, c in enumerate(df_feats.columns, start=1):  # skip constant at 0
            vals.append((c, vif(X_.values, i)))
        out = pd.DataFrame(vals, columns=["feature", "VIF"]).sort_values("VIF", ascending=False)
        return out

    # work on TRAIN features only
    feats = X_train.columns.tolist()
    Xv = X_train[feats].copy()

    while True:
        vif_df = compute_vif(Xv)
        display(vif_df)
        hi = vif_df.iloc[0]
        if hi["VIF"] > 10 and len(Xv.columns) > 2:
            print(f"Dropping '{hi['feature']}' due to high VIF={hi['VIF']:.2f}")
            Xv = Xv.drop(columns=[hi["feature"]])
        else:
            break

    FEATURES_FINAL = Xv.columns.tolist()

except Exception as e:
    print("statsmodels unavailable; falling back to correlation check. Err:", e)
    corr = X_train.corr().abs()
    upper = corr.where(np.triu(np.ones(corr.shape), k=1).astype(bool))
    to_drop = [c for c in upper.columns if any(upper[c] > 0.95)]
    FEATURES_FINAL = [c for c in X_train.columns if c not in to_drop]
    print("Dropped (corr>0.95):", to_drop)

print("Final feature set:", FEATURES_FINAL)

Feature Diagnostics Variance Inflation Factors (VIF)

This table reports VIF values for the explanatory variables used in the modelling step (lag-1 daily returns of global indices and VIX). VIF measures how strongly a feature is linearly explained by the remaining features; values near 1 indicate independence, while values above 5 (and especially >10) suggest problematic multicollinearity.

Results

  • Nasdaq_Return_lag1: 3.50
  • VIX_Return_lag1: 1.94
  • DAX_Return_lag1: 1.83
  • Nikkei_Return_lag1: 1.26
  • HangSeng_Return_lag1: 1.25

Interpretation

All VIFs are well below 5, indicating that multicollinearity is not a material concern for the current specification. The relatively higher VIFs for Dow Jones and Nasdaq are expected given their strong mutual correlation; however, the values remain within acceptable bounds and do not warrant feature removal.

Implications for Modelling

  • Proceed with the current feature set for logistic/ML models without regularization strictly for multicollinearity control.
  • If additional lags or interaction terms are introduced, re-check VIFs; these could push U.S. index VIFs closer to the caution zone.
  • Regularized models (e.g., L1/L2) can further mitigate any residual redundancy and aid interpretability.

Summary

The VIF diagnostic confirms that the predictors provide complementary information with only modest overlap (primarily between U.S. indices). The feature set is therefore statistically sound for the subsequent predictive modelling phases.

7) Choose threshold to balance sensitivity & specificity (Train)

In[74]:
# Step 7  Optimal threshold
import numpy as np
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix, precision_score, recall_score, f1_score, accuracy_score

youden = tpr_tr - fpr_tr
best_idx = int(np.argmax(youden))
THRESHOLD = float(thr_tr[best_idx])

def metrics_at_threshold(y_true, y_prob, thr):
    y_pred_thr = (y_prob >= thr).astype(int)
    tn, fp, fn, tp = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred_thr).ravel()
    sens = tp/(tp+fn) if (tp+fn)>0 else 0.0
    spec = tn/(tn+fp) if (tn+fp)>0 else 0.0
    return {
        "threshold": thr,
        "accuracy": accuracy_score(y_true, y_pred_thr),
        "precision": precision_score(y_true, y_pred_thr, zero_division=0),
        "recall_sensitivity": sens,
        "specificity": spec,
        "f1": f1_score(y_true, y_pred_thr, zero_division=0),
        "confusion_matrix": [[tn, fp],[fn, tp]]
    }

train_thr_metrics = metrics_at_threshold(y_train, y_prob_tr, THRESHOLD)
print("")
print(f"Chosen TRAIN threshold (Youdens J): {THRESHOLD:.3f}")
print("")

for k, v in train_thr_metrics.items():
    if k != "confusion_matrix":
        print(f"{k:25s}: {v:.3f}" if isinstance(v, (float, int)) else f"{k:25s}: {v}")
print("Confusion Matrix:", train_thr_metrics["confusion_matrix"])
print("")

Text Processing Corpus Construction & Cleaning (X/Twitter Data)

The text dataset used for this analysis was generated in Python as a simulated collection of X / Twitter-style market commentary. Because live platform data was not available in a structured economic feed, a synthetic corpus was created to mimic realistic intraday financial tweets based on market movements. This simulated dataset provides a controlled and repeatable foundation for downstream NLP analysis.

Cleaning Pipeline

  • Emoji & dingbat removal: A custom regex pattern was defined to capture full emoji blocks, dingbats, miscellaneous symbols and arrows. The function remove_all_emoji_like() applies this pattern to each tweet, stripping out all emoji-like characters to avoid noise that does not contribute to economic interpretation.
  • Lowercasing: All text in the corpus (corp) was converted to .lower(). This ensures that words such as Nifty and nifty are treated as the same token, preventing artificial duplication due to case differences.
  • Punctuation removal: Using string.punctuation and str.maketrans(), a translation map was created and applied so that commas, periods, hashtags, and other punctuation marks are removed. This step focuses the corpus on lexical content rather than tweet formatting.
  • Digit removal: A similar translation map based on string.digits was used to strip out numeric characters. This prevents raw numbers (dates, levels, codes) from dominating frequency counts where the interest is primarily in directional language (e.g., bullish, flat, bearish).
  • Tokenisation & stopword filtering: For each cleaned sentence, NLTKs word_tokenize was applied to split the text into individual tokens. Standard English stopwords from nltk.corpus.stopwords.words('english') were removed, and the remaining tokens were stored as filtered_sentence in a list fs.
  • Domain-specific stopword extension: To further refine the corpus, a set of high-frequency but low-value financial terms was added to the stopword list. These included nifty, nifty50, #nifty50, $nifty, nse, and time-of-day markers such as morning and eod. These words appear in nearly every post due to the datasets intraday-market nature and would otherwise overshadow more meaningful vocabulary. After extending stop_words, the filtering step was reapplied so that each token list in fs contains only linguistically informative terms.

Interpretation

  • The pipeline transforms noisy, emoji-rich X posts into a clean economic language corpus, where each entry is a list of meaningful tokens describing market conditions (e.g., flat yields no big flows yet bearish markets).
  • Removing emojis, punctuation, digits, and generic market identifiers dramatically improves the reliability of downstream statistics such as word frequencies, co-occurrences, sentiment, and topic patterns.
  • The final token list fs forms a robust foundation for sentiment analysis, topic extraction, and linking tweet language to market movements.

from nltk.sentiment.vader import SentimentIntensityAnalyzer
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Initialize
sid = SentimentIntensityAnalyzer()

# Process sentiment for each sentence
results = []
for sentence in text:
    ss = sid.polarity_scores(sentence)
    results.append({
        "sentence": sentence,
        "compound": ss['compound'],
        "negative": ss['neg'],
        "neutral": ss['neu'],
        "positive": ss['pos']
    })

sent_df = pd.DataFrame(results)

# Label function
def label_sentiment(c):
    if c <= -0.05:
        return "Negative"
    elif c >= 0.05:
        return "Positive"
    else:
        return "Neutral"

sent_df["sentiment"] = sent_df["compound"].apply(label_sentiment)

Sentiment Analysis VADER Lexicon (Simulated Market Commentary)

To characterise the emotional tone of the simulated X/Twitter-style market updates, the VADER sentiment analyser was applied to each sentence in the corpus. VADER is well suited for short, informal, finance-oriented snippets as it captures both polarity and intensity without requiring model training.

Processing Pipeline

  • VADER polarity scoring: Each sentence was passed through SentimentIntensityAnalyzer(), producing four key metrics: negative, neutral, positive, and a compound score summarising overall polarity.
  • Sentiment labelling: The compound score was mapped into categorical labels (Negative, Neutral, Positive) using a standard thresholding rule: values 0.05 classified as Negative, 0.05 as Positive, and those in between as Neutral.
  • Data structuring: All sentiment scores, original sentences, and labels were stored in a pandas DataFrame (sent_df) for plotting and statistical inspection.

Visualisations

  • Bar Chart Sentiment Distribution: A countplot contrasts the volume of Positive, Neutral, and Negative sentences. In this dataset, Positive commentary is the most frequent, followed by Negative, with Neutral forming the smallest share. This aligns with the tone of short-form trading updates, which often emphasise direction, opportunity, or caution.
  • Histogram & KDE Compound Score Distribution: A histogram with an overlaid KDE curve illustrates how sentiment intensity varies across the corpus. The distribution reveals a balanced spread of polarity, with slight clustering around both mild positivity and mild negativity. This pattern reflects the natural ebb and flow of trading commentary during intraday market movement.
  • Pie Chart Sentiment Breakdown: A pie chart summarises the proportion of each sentiment class. Positive sentences dominate, followed by a substantial Negative portion, while Neutral statements form a much smaller wedge. This reinforces earlier observations that market-focused tweets tend to favour directional expression rather than emotionally neutral phrasing.

Interpretation

  • The overall sentiment landscape of the simulated tweets shows a healthy mix of market optimism and caution, mirroring real intraday trading environments.
  • The compound score distribution verifies that the model captures subtle fluctuations in tone rather than clustering around extremes, which is consistent with realistic financial commentary.
  • These sentiment outputs provide a strong foundation for further modelling, such as linking sentiment trends to price direction, volatility shifts, or breakout probability in later predictive phases.
